COUNT ONE - 1 M.S.C. § 2101 - FIRST DEGREE MURDER
OFFENSE TYPE - FELONY
AGAINST DEFENDANT - CLUGGAS
On or about the 27th of September 2024, Defendant cluggas did unlawfully, and with malice
aforethought, intentionally kill a member of Military Police inside National Guard Fort, without
premeditation.

Did the State mean to charge first degree murder? It looks like they omitted the element of premeditation and specifically stated "without premeditation" while premeditation is a required element of premeditated first degree murder. Even if it was felony murder (which is still fdm), I don't find that the charging language tracks for that either.

I'd just like to add that malice aforethought and premeditation are not synonymous. I see this a lot on the State's CIs. They are similar but not synonymous—premeditation is a required element of first degree murder per statute and it's not alleged here.

Deverus 2024-10-28 09:02 p.m.
if i may;

the statute for first degree murder, per the mayflower state code, reads "any player who intentionally, and maliciously kills another player with premeditation or who kills whilst in the commission of a felony, or kills a uniformed or clearly identifiable civil servant in the commission of their duties..."

the victim, devaxit, is (or was) a military police officer within the mayflower national guard, and was both uniformed and clearly identifiable in the commission of their lawful duties at the time of the incident.

while the state is amenable to a revision of the charging information, we still intend to charge with FDM under the written statute.

MINUTE ORDER: Return on Summons/Initial Appearance/Arraignment as to Counts 1 and 2 held on 10/30/2024. zerluc and frostbleed appeared on behalf of defendant cluggas. Plea of Not Guilty entered as to Counts 1 and 2. It is further ORDERED AND ADJUDGED that the Court confirms the State's obligation to disclose to the defendant all exculpatory evidence—namely, evidence that favors the defendant or casts doubt on the State's case—as required by the principles established in Brady v. Maryland, 373 U.S. 83 (1963) and its progeny. The State is hereby ORDERED to fulfill this obligation. The State has a duty to disclose any evidence that negates the defendant's guilt, affects the credibility of a witness, or could potentially reduce a sentence. The defendant is entitled to this information without needing to make a request. Failure to disclose exculpatory evidence in a timely manner may result in consequences, including, but not limited to, exclusion of evidence, dismissal of the information, contempt proceedings, disciplinary action, or sanctions by the Court. Signed by Judge sadoimpacto on 10/30/2024.
